findings.suggested_fix:
Bound nesting depth BEFORE any recursive walker runs, and make the walkers non-recursive or depth-limited. Concretely: (1) In _strict_load, after json.loads, run an explicit iterative depth check and return _err('SCHEMA_STRUCTURE'/'PARSE_ERROR', '<root>', 'nesting too deep') if depth exceeds a small cap (e.g. 64), which is far more than any legitimate ACMG submission needs. (2) Convert _nonfinite_errors and _verdict_key_errors to explicit-stack iterative traversals (push (obj, path) onto a list). (3) Wrap the whole body of validate_evidence in a try/except (RecursionError, Exception) that returns a structured {valid:false, error_code:'PARSE_ERROR'/'SCHEMA_STRUCTURE', ...} so the function can never raise. Example depth guard:

    def _max_depth(o, d=0):
        stack=[(o,d)]; m=d
        while stack:
            x,dd=stack.pop(); m=max(m,dd)
            if isinstance(x,dict): stack+=[(v,dd+1) for v in x.values()]
            elif isinstance(x,list): stack+=[(v,dd+1) for v in x]
        return m
    if _max_depth(obj) > 64:
        return None, [_err('SCHEMA_STRUCTURE','<root>','nesting exceeds maximum depth')]

